title: Interphase
description: Interphase of the cell cycle, including G₁, S, and G₂ phases. How the cell replicates its DNA before mitosis.

title: Mendel and his peas
description: How Austrian monk Gregor Mendel laid the foundations of genetics. Mendel's life, experiments, and pea plants.

title: Module 5: Examples of functions from geometry
description: "Students are introduced to functions in the context of linear equations and area/volume formulas in Module 5. They define, evaluate, and compare functions using equations of lines as a source of linear functions and area and volume formulas as a source of non-linear functions. " Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Module 1: Relationships between quantities and reasoning with equations and their graphs
description: "In this module students analyze and explain precisely the process of solving an equation.  Through repeated reasoning, students develop fluency in writing, interpreting, and translating between various forms of linear equations and inequalities and make conjectures about the form that a linear equation might take in a solution to a problem.  They reason abstractly and quantitatively by choosing and interpreting units in the context of creating equations in two variables to represent relationships between quantities.  They master the solution of linear equations and apply related solution techniques and the properties of exponents to the creation and solution of simple exponential equations.  They learn the terminology specific to polynomials and understand that polynomials form a system analogous to the integers." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: The law of segregation
description: Mendel's law of segregation. Genotype, phenotype, and alleles. Heterozygous/homozygous. 2 x 2 Punnett squares.

title: Phases of the cell cycle
description: The cell cycle is composed of interphase (G₁, S, and G₂ phases), followed by the mitotic phase (mitosis and cytokinesis), and G₀ phase.

title: Module 6: Linear functions
description: "In Module 6, students return to linear functions in the context of statistics and probability as bivariate data provides support in the use of linear functions. " Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: The law of independent assortment
description: Mendel's law of independent assortment. Dihybrid crosses. 4 x 4 Punnett squares.

title: Module 2: Descriptive statistics
description: "In this module, students reconnect with and deepen their understanding of statistics and probability concepts first introduced in Grades 6, 7, and 8. Students develop a set of tools for understanding and interpreting variability in data, and begin to make more informed decisions from data. They work with data distributions of various shapes, centers, and spreads. Students build on their experience with bivariate quantitative data from Grade 8. This module sets the stage for more extensive work with sampling and inference in later grades." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Mitosis
description: Mitosis is how cells divide! Learn what happens in all the phases of mitosis: prophase, metaphase, anaphase, and telophase.

title: Estimating derivatives of a function at a point
Module 7: Introduction to irrational numbers using geometry
description: "By Module 7 students have been using the Pythagorean Theorem for several months. They are sufficiently prepared to learn and explain a proof of the theorem on their own. The Pythagorean Theorem is also used to motivate a discussion of irrational square roots (irrational cube roots are introduced via volume of a sphere). Thus, as the year began with looking at the number system, so it concludes with students understanding irrational numbers and ways to represent them (radicals, non-repeating decimal expansions) on the real number line. " Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Probabilities in genetics
description: The sum rule and product rule. Applying these rules to solve genetics problems involving many genes.

title: Module 3: Linear and exponential functions
description: "In earlier grades, students define, evaluate, and compare functions and use them to model relationships between quantities. In this module, students extend their study of functions to include function notation and the concepts of domain and range. They explore many examples of functions and their graphs, focusing on the contrast between linear and exponential functions. They interpret functions given graphically, numerically, symbolically, and verbally; translate between representations; and understand the limitations of various representations." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Phases of mitosis
description: How a cell divides to make two genetically identical cells. Prophase, metaphase, anaphase, and telophase.

title: Monohybrid punnett squares
description: Test your knowledge of punnett squares!

title: Module 4: Polynomial and quadratic expressions, equations, and functions
description: "In earlier modules, students analyze the process of solving equations and developing fluency in writing, interpreting, and translating between various forms of linear equations (Module 1) and linear and exponential functions (Module 3). These experiences combined with modeling with data (Module 2), set the stage for Module 4. Here students continue to interpret expressions, create equations, rewrite equations and functions in different but equivalent forms, and graph and interpret functions, but this time using polynomial functions, and more specifically quadratic functions, as well as square root and cube root functions." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Mitosis questions
description: Use these questions to check your understanding of mitosis!

title: Module 5: A synthesis of modeling with equations and functions
description: "In Module 5, students synthesize what they have learned during the year about functions to select the correct function type in a series of modeling problems. Students no longer have the benefit of a module or lesson title that includes function type to guide them in their choices. Skills and knowledge from the previous modules will support the requirements of this module, including writing, rewriting, comparing, and graphing functions and interpretation of the parameters of an equation. Students must also draw on their study of statistics in Module 2, using graphs and functions to model a context presented with data and/or tables of values. In this module, the modeling cycle is used  as the organizing structure, rather than function type." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Bacterial binary fission
description: Bacterial binary fission is the process that bacteria use to carry out cell division. Learn the steps of binary fission, including copying the bacterial chromosome and forming a new cell wall.

title: Structure of DNA
description: DNA is the molecule that carries heredity information for all living things on Earth. Learn more about the structure of this amazing molecule and how it carries information.

title: Variations on Mendelian genetics
description: Mendel's model forms the core of our modern understanding of inheritance. However, in the 150 years since it was first proposed, the model has been revised and extended, and these revisions are important in explaining the inheritance patterns we see around us. Learn more about variations on Mendel's model.

title: Meiosis
description: Normal human body cells have two complete sets of chromosomes, while sperm and egg cells have just one set each. How, then, does a normal body cell give rise to sperm or eggs? The answer lies in a two-step division process called meiosis. Learn more about meiosis and how it contributes to genetic variation in humans (and other sexually reproducing organisms).

title: Comparing mitosis and meiosis
description: Comparison of the processes of mitosis and meiosis.

title: Discovery of DNA
description: Today, we know that DNA is the genetic material: the molecule that bears genes, is passed from parents to children, and provides instructions for the growth and functioning of living organisms. But scientists didn’t always know this. In fact, for many years, researchers thought that protein would turn out to be the genetic material! Learn more about the properties of DNA and how it was identified as the hereditary molecule.

title: Counting in order
description: Learn how to count without making mistakes.

title: Phases of meiosis II
description: How sister chromatids separate to form gametes. Prophase II, metaphase II, anaphase II, telophase II.

title: DNA as the "transforming principle"
description: How Griffith and later Avery, McCarty and MacLeod found strong evidence that DNA is the "transforming principle" that encodes genetic information.

title: Count in order
description: Practice counting without making mistakes.

title: Meiosis
description: How meiosis reduces chromosome number by half: crossing over, meiosis I, meiosis II, and genetic variation.

title: Hershey and Chase: DNA is the genetic material
description: How Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase showed conclusively that DNA is the genetic material.

title: Non-Mendelian genetics
description: Test your knowledge on non-Mendelian genetics!

title: Find 1 more or 1 less than a number
description: Practice finding one more or one less than a number.

title: Cell cycle regulation, cancer, and stem cells
description: Cells in your body are dividing all the time. If they're healthy cells, they divide in a carefully controlled way, proceeding with division only when conditions are right. Cancer cells, on the other hand, divide in an uncontrolled way. Learn more about cell cycle control, cancer cells, and stem cells.

title: Thomas Hunt Morgan and fruit flies
description: Thomas Hunt Morgan's pioneering fruit fly work that helped validate the chromosomal theory of inheritance.

title: Discovery of the structure of DNA
description: The structure of DNA double helix and how it was discovered. Chargaff, Watson and Crick, and Wilkins and Franklin.

title: Embryonic stem cells
description: An overview of early development of a zygote to an embryo. Embryonic and somatic stem cells.

title: Number grid
description: Sal goes through all the numbers from 0 to 100 and shows some interesting patterns.

title: The chromosomal basis of inheritance
description: Thomas Hunt Morgan's experiments. The fruit fly (Drosophila melanogaster) as a model system.

title: Discovery of DNA
description: Test your knowledge on the events and people involved in the discovery of DNA!

title: Cell cycle checkpoints
description: How cells use checkpoints at the end of G1 phase, end of G2 phase, and partway through M phase (the spindle checkpoint) to regulate the cell cycle.

title: Missing numbers between 0 and 120
description: Sal finds missing numbers between 0 and 120.

title: Genetic linkage & mapping
description: What it means for genes to be linked. How to determine recombination frequency for a pair of genes.

title: DNA replication
description: When you make a copy of something, how perfect does the copy need to be? If that something is your DNA, the answer is, pretty perfect! Errors during DNA copying can lead to cancer and other health conditions. Learn how cells use a group of different enzymes to accurately copy their DNA, and how they detect and repair copying errors and DNA damage.

title: Cell cycle regulators
description: The core control system of the cell cycle. Cyclins, cyclin-dependent kinases (Cdks), and the APC/C.

title: Recombination frequency and gene mapping
description: Test your knowledge on recombination frequency and gene mapping!

title: Leading and lagging strands in DNA replication
description: Roles of DNA polymerase, primase, ligase, helicase and topoisomerase in DNA replication. An explanation of leading and lagging strands.

title: Cancer
description: An introduction to what cancer is and how it is the by-product of broken DNA replication.

title: Numbers to 120
description: Practice finding missing numbers in a list of numbers between 0 and 120.

title: Sex linkage, chromosomal mutations, & non-nuclear inheritance
description: What are the consequences of genes being carried on chromosomes? Well, all sorts of interesting stuff! We can see sex linkage when genes are on X or Y chromosomes, genetic disorders when too few or too many chromosomes are inherited, and unusual inheritance patterns when our genes are in the chromosomes of mitochondria or chloroplasts.

title: Speed and precision of DNA replication
description: Sal reflects on the amazing speed and precision with which DNA replication takes place.

title: Cancer and the cell cycle
description: How cancer can be linked to overactive positive cell cycle regulators (oncogenes) or inactive negative regulators (tumor suppressors).

title: Counting by tens
description: Practice counting by tens using numbers and ten frames.

title: Inheritance of mitochondrial and chloroplast DNA
description: Mitochondrial and chloroplast DNA and why its inheritance does not follow Mendelian patterns.

title: X-inactivation and aneuploidy
description: Test your knowledge on X-inactivation and aneuploidy!

title: Module 3: Extending to three dimensions
description: "Module 3, Extending to Three Dimensions, builds on students’ understanding of congruence in Module 1 and similarity in Module 2 to prove volume formulas for solids." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Central dogma and the genetic code
description: Get an overview of the "central dogma" of molecular biology! Learn how a gene's DNA is copied into RNA (transcription), which is then "decoded" to specify the amino acid sequence of a protein (translation).

title: Intro to gene expression (central dogma)
description: How genes in DNA can provide instructions for proteins. The central dogma of molecular biology: DNA → RNA → protein.

title: Comparing numbers to 10
description: Practice saying if one number is less than or greater than another number. Numbers are between 0 and 10.

title: The genetic code
description: The genetic code links groups of nucleotides in an mRNA to amino acids in a protein. Start codons, stop codons, reading frame.

title: One gene, one enzyme
description: Historical experiments: Garrod's studies of alkaptonuria,  Beadle and Tatum's work with Neurospora mutants.

title: Intro to subtraction
description: Sal talks about what it means to subtract. The examples he uses are 4-3 and 5-2.

title: Airbus A380 take-off distance
description: How long of a runway does an A380 need?

title: Sex-linked traits
description: Sex-linked traits are associated with genes found on sex chromosomes. In humans, the sex chromosomes are X and Y. Because the X-chromosome is larger, X-linked traits are more common than Y-linked traits. An example of a sex-linked trait is red-green colorblindness, which is carried on the X-chromosome. Because males only have one X-chromosome, they have a higher chance of having red-green colorblindness.

title: Cell cycle regulation
description: Test your knowledge on methods of cell cycle regulation!

title: Molecular mechanism of DNA replication
description: Roles of DNA polymerases and other replication enzymes. Leading and lagging strands and Okazaki fragments.

title: Count tens
description: Practice counting by tens.

title: X-linked inheritance
description: Chromosomal basis of sex determination. X and Y chromosomes, X-linkage.

title: Apoptosis
description: How apoptosis is different from cell death by injury. Role in development and body maintenance.

title: Counting objects
description: Learn to count up to 20 objects.

title: Mode of DNA replication: Meselson-Stahl experiment
description: A key historical experiment that demonstrated the semi-conservative mechanism of DNA replication.

title: Sex-linked traits
description: Test your knowledge on sex-linked traits!

title: Apoptosis
description: Programmed cell death and how it is different from necrosis (cell death due to injury).

title: Counting in pictures
description: Sal counts the number of objects in pictures.

title: X-inactivation
description: How XX human females (and other female mammals) shut down one of their X chromosomes in each cell. Disorders of sex chromosome number: Klinefelter, triple X, and Turner syndromes.

title: DNA proofreading and repair
description: Mechanisms to correct errors during DNA replication and to repair DNA damage over the cell's lifetime.

title: Apoptosis
description: Test your knowledge on the process of apoptosis!

title: Count in pictures
description: Practice counting objects in pictures.

title: Aneuploidy & chromosomal rearrangements
description: Aneuploidy and nondisjunction. Down syndrome and related disorders. Chromosomal rearrangements.

title: Telomeres and telomerase
description: Telomeres as protective "caps" on the tips of eukaryotic chromosomes. How telomerase extends telomeres.

title: Counting objects 1
description: Learn to count groups of whales, sheep, and flowers.

title: Module 1: Congruence, proof, and constructions
description: "Module 1 embodies critical changes in Geometry as outlined by the Common Core. The heart of the module is the study of transformations and the role transformations play in defining congruence. The topic of transformations is introduced in a primarily experiential manner in Grade 8 and is formalized in Grade 10 with the use of precise language. The need for clear use of language is emphasized through vocabulary, the process of writing steps to perform constructions, and ultimately as part of the proof-writing process." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Count objects 1
description: Practice counting up to 20 objects. Objects are organized neatly into rows and columns.

title: Molecular basis of genetics
description: Mendel's "heritable factors," which we now call genes, are actually regions of DNA found on chromosomes. Learn how a gene can specify a protein through the processes of transcription and translation, and how alleles are versions of a gene that have different DNA sequences.

title: Module 2: Similarity, proof, and trigonometry
description: "Just as rigid motions are used to define congruence in Module 1, so dilations are added to define similarity in Module 2.  To be able to discuss similarity, students must first have a clear understanding of how dilations behave.  This is done in two parts, by studying how dilations yield scale drawings and reasoning why the properties of dilations must be true. Once dilations are clearly established, similarity transformations are defined and length and angle relationships are examined, yielding triangle similarity criteria.  An in-depth look at similarity within right triangles follows, and finally the module ends with a study of right triangle trigonometry." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Counting objects 2
description: Learn to count dogs, mice, and cookies in random patterns.

title: Count objects 2
description: Practice counting up to 20 objects in random patterns.

title: Alleles and genes
description: A gene as a stretch of DNA on a chromosome. Alleles as versions (sequence variants) of a gene.

title: Comparing small numbers
description: Learn to compare numbers between 0 and 10.

title: Module 4: Connecting algebra and geometry through coordinates
description: "In this module, students explore and experience the utility of analyzing algebra and geometry challenges through the framework of coordinates. The module opens with a modeling challenge, one that reoccurs throughout the lessons, to use coordinate geometry to program the motion of a robot that is bound within a certain polygonal region of the plane—the room in which it sits. To set the stage for complex work in analytic geometry (computing coordinates of points of intersection of lines and line segments or the coordinates of points that divide given segments in specific length ratios, and so on), students will describe the region via systems of algebraic inequalities and work to constrain the robot motion along line segments within the region." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Comparing numbers of objects
description: Sal talks about what "more than" and "less than" mean.

title: Module 5: Circles with and without coordinates
description: "This module brings together the ideas of similarity and congruence and the properties of length, area, and geometric constructions studied throughout the year.  It also includes the specific properties of triangles, special quadrilaterals, parallel lines and transversals, and rigid motions established and built upon throughout this mathematical story.  This module's focus is on the possible geometric relationships between a pair of intersecting lines and a circle drawn on the page." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Compare numbers of objects 1
description: Practice counting which group has more objects.

title: Comparing numbers on the number line
description: Sal uses number line to compare numbers less than or equal to 10.

title: Teens
description: Learn how teen numbers work.

title: Module 1: Polynomial, rational, and radical relationships
description: "Students connect polynomial arithmetic to computations with whole numbers and integers.  Students learn that the arithmetic of rational expressions is governed by the same rules as the arithmetic of rational numbers.  This unit helps students see connections between solutions to polynomial equations, zeros of polynomials, and graphs of polynomial functions.  Polynomial equations are solved over the set of complex numbers, leading to a beginning understanding of the fundamental theorem of algebra.  Application and modeling problems connect multiple representations and include both real world and purely mathematical situations." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Central dogma
description: Test your knowledge on the central dogma of biology!

title: Subtract within 5
description: Subtract small numbers. All answers are less than 5.

title: Module 2: Trigonometric functions
description: "Module 2 builds on students’ previous work with units and with functions from Algebra I, and with trigonometric ratios and circles from high school Geometry. The heart of the module is the study of precise definitions of sine and cosine (as well as tangent and the co-functions) using transformational geometry from high school Geometry. This precision leads to a discussion of a mathematically natural unit of rotational measure, a radian, and students begin to build fluency with the values of the trigonometric functions in terms of radians. Students graph sinusoidal and other trigonometric functions, and use the graphs to help in modeling and discovering properties of trigonometric functions. The study of the properties culminates in the proof of the Pythagorean identity and other trigonometric identities." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Transcription
description: Transcription is the first step in gene expression. It involves copying, or transcribing, the DNA sequence of a gene into the similar "alphabet" of RNA nucleotides. Learn more about this crucial cellular process.

title: Making small numbers
description: Learn to make numbers from other numbers by adding. Numbers used are 10 or less.

title: Making 5
description: Learn how to add numbers to make the number five.

title: Module 3: Exponential and logarithmic functions
description: "In this module, students synthesize and generalize what they have learned about a variety of function families.  They extend the domain of exponential functions to the entire real line (N-RN.A.1) and then extend their work with these functions to include solving exponential equations with logarithms (F-LE.A.4).  They explore (with appropriate tools) the effects of transformations on graphs of exponential and logarithmic functions.  They notice that the transformations on a graph of a logarithmic function relate to the logarithmic properties (F-BF.B.3).  Students identify appropriate types of functions to model a situation.  They adjust parameters to improve the model, and they compare models by analyzing appropriateness of fit and making judgments about the domain over which a model is a good fit.  The description of modeling as, “the process of choosing and using mathematics and statistics to analyze empirical situations, to understand them better, and to make decisions,” is at the heart of this module.  In particular, through repeated opportunities in working through the modeling cycle (see page 61 of the CCLS), students acquire the insight that the same mathematical or statistical structure can sometimes model seemingly different situations." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Transcription and mRNA processing
description: Introduction to transcription including the role of RNA polymerase, promoters, terminators, introns and exons.

title: Making 5
description: Practice adding numbers to make 5.

title: Adding with regrouping
description: Sal adds 35 + 27 thinking about place value.

title: Subtraction word problem: crayons
description: Sal solves a subtraction word problem with numbers less than 100.

title: Addition word problem: spots
description: Sal solves a word problem with the term "more".

title: Module 4: Inferences and conclusions from data
description: "Students build a formal understanding of probability, considering complex events such as unions, intersections, and complements as well as the concept of independence and conditional probability.  The idea of using a smooth curve to model a data distribution is introduced along with using tables and technology to find areas under a normal curve.  Students make inferences and justify conclusions from sample surveys, experiments, and observational studies.  Data is used from random samples to estimate a population mean or proportion.  Students calculate margin of error and interpret it in context.  Given data from a statistical experiment, students use simulation to create a randomization distribution and use it to determine if there is a significant difference between two treatments." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Gene regulation in bacteria
description: Do you think of bacteria as boring blobs? How about as little calculators? Bacterial gene regulation networks essentially perform logic operations using proteins and DNA. Learn more about how bacterial genes are organized and how their expression is regulated.

title: Making small numbers in different ways
description: Practice making a number by adding other numbers. All numbers in these problems are less than 10.

title: Operons and gene regulation in bacteria
description: Looking at how regulatory DNA sequences can repress or promote gene transcription (particularly in bacteria operons).

title: Overview of transcription
description: In transcription, the DNA sequence of a gene is transcribed (copied out) to make an RNA molecule.

title: Making 10
description: Learn how to make the number 10 from two smaller numbers.

title: Trp operon
description: The trp operon is a well-studied operon when it comes to gene regulation. It is involved in the biosynthesis of the amino acid tryptophan.

title: Stages of transcription
description: An in-depth looks at how transcription works. Initiation (promoters), elongation, and termination.

title: Getting to 10 by filling boxes
description: Sal shows how to add two numbers to make 10. He uses 3 + ___ = 10 and 6 + ___ = 10 as examples.

title: Lac operon
description: Overview of gene regulation in the Lac operon. Discussion of CAP, cAMP, lac repressor and allolactose in regulation of lac operon.

title: Eukaryotic pre-mRNA processing
description: 5' cap and poly-A tail. Splicing, introns, and exons.

title: Make 10 (grids and number bonds)
description: Practice adding numbers to make 10. These problems show grids to help you out.

title: Overview: Gene regulation in bacteria
description: Overview of operons, regulatory DNA sequences, & regulatory genes. Repressor & activator proteins.

title: Transcription
description: Test your knowledge on the process of transcription!

title: Adding to 10
description: Sal finds out how many bananas we need to add to 3 bananas to make 10 bananas.

title: Teens as sums with 10
description: Sal looks at the 1 in each teen number and thinks about what it really means.

title: Translation
description: In translation, the nucleotide sequence of an mRNA is "decoded" to specify the sequence of amino acids in a protein. Learn more about the steps of this process and the molecules that carry it out.

title: The lac operon
description: Regulation of genes for lactose utilization. lac repressor, catabolite activator protein, and cAMP.

title: Make 10
description: Practice adding numbers to make 10.

title: Teen numbers: monkeys
description: Sal breaks the number 18 into 10 and 8.

title: The trp operon
description: How the trp repressor controls expression gene expression. Feedback inhibition & attenuation.

title: Translation (mRNA to protein)
description: A deep dive into how mRNA is translated into proteins with the help of ribosomes and tRNA.

title: Put together, take apart
description: When we add, we put together. When we subtract, we take apart. Numbers used are 10 or less.

title: Teen numbers
description: Practice thinking of teen numbers as a ten plus some ones.

title: Add and subtract: pieces of fruit
description: Sal adds fruit and subtracts fruit. The examples he uses are 5+3 and 5-3.

title: Gene regulation in bacteria
description: Test your knowledge on gene regulation in bacteria and the operon!

title: Overview of translation
description: How the nucleotide sequence of an mRNA is translated into the amino acid sequence of a polypeptide (protein).

title: Tens
description: Learn to see two-digit numbers as tens and ones.

title: Addition and subtraction within 10
description: Sal solves addition and subtraction problems with number 10 or less.

title: Gene regulation in eukaryotes
description: In multicellular eukaryotes (like you!), each type of cell in the body must express its own unique set of genes. Learn more about the many ways that eukaryotic gene expression can be regulated.

title: tRNAs and ribosomes
description: Structure and roles of transfer RNAs and ribosomes. Codons, anticodons, and wobble. Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases.

title: Intro to place value
description: Sal uses the number 37 to explain why we use a "ones place" and a "tens place" when writing numbers.

title: Compare 2-digit numbers
description: Practice comparing numbers (within 100) using the symbols <, >, and =.

title: Intro to biotechnology
description: What biotechnology is. Overview of DNA technology. Ethical questions in biotechnology.

title: Gel electrophoresis
description: A technique used to separate DNA fragments and other macromolecules by size and charge.

title: Overview: Eukaryotic gene regulation
description: How different genes are expressed in different cell types. The big picture of eukaryotic gene regulation.

title: Add within 10
description: Practice adding by "putting together" (with numbers less than 10).

title: Stages of translation
description: An in-depth look how polypeptides (proteins) are made. Initiation, elongation, and termination.

title: Place value example: 25
description: Sal shows 25 as 2 tens and 5 ones.

title: Transcription factors
description: General and specific transcription factors. Transcription initiation complex & looping. Combinatorial regulation.

title: Subtract within 10
description: Practice subtracting by "taking apart" (with numbers less than 10).

title: Protein targeting
description: How molecular labels are used to direct proteins to different parts of the cell (and to the cell exterior).

title: Place value example: 42
description: Sal shows 42 as 4 tens and 2 ones.

title: Regulation after transcription
description: Alternative splicing, miRNAs and siRNAs, translation initiation factors, & protein modifications.

title: Relate addition and subtraction
description: Learn how to addition and subtraction are related. Numbers used are 10 or less.

title: Translation
description: Test your knowledge on the process of translation!

title: Groups of ten objects
description: Practice grouping objects by tens.

title: Gene regulation in eukaryotes
description: Test your knowledge on gene regulation in eukaryotes!

title: Relating addition and subtraction
description: Sal shows the relationship between 2+3=5, 5-2=3, and 5-3=2.

title: Tens and ones
description: Practice thinking about 2-digit numbers as tens and ones.

title: Relate addition and subtraction
description: Practice seeing how addition and subtraction are related.

title: 2-digit place value challenge
description: Practice breaking numbers apart into tens and ones.

title: Comparing 2-digit numbers
description: Learn how to compare two-digit numbers by thinking about place value (tens and ones).

title: Addition and subtraction word problems
description: Learn how to solve addition and subtraction word problems with small numbers. Numbers used are 10 or less.

title: Module 1: Complex numbers and transformations
description: "Module 1 sets the stage for expanding students' understanding of transformations by exploring the notion of linearity.  This leads to the study of complex numbers and linear transformations in the complex plane.  The teacher materials consist of the teacher pages including exit tickets, exit ticket solutions, and all student materials with solutions for each lesson in Module 1." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Greater than and less than symbols
description: Greater than and less than symbols can be used to compare numbers and expressions. The greater than symbol is >. So, 9>7 is read as '9 is greater than 7'. The less than symbol is <. Two other comparison symbols are ≥ (greater than or equal to) and ≤ (less than or equal to).

title: Addition word problems within 10
description: Sal solves word problems by adding small numbers (numbers 10 or less).

title: Intro to biotechnology
description: What is biotechnology? Learn how biotechnology can include a wide range of products and applications, from penicillin to beer to gene therapy, and get an overview of modern DNA technologies.

title: Module 2: Vectors and matrices
description: "Module 2 extends the concept of matrices introduced in Module 1.  Students look at incidence relationships in networks and encode information about them via high-dimensional matrices.  Matrix properties are studied as well as the role of the zero and identity matrices.  Students then use matrices to study and solve higher order systems of equations.  Vectors are introduced, and students study the arithmetic of vectors and vector magnitude.  The module ends as students program video games using matrices and vectors." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Addition word problems within 10
description: Practice solving word problems by adding small numbers (numbers 10 or less).

title: Module 3: Rational and exponential functions
description: "Students revisit the fundamental theorem of algebra as they explore complex roots of polynomial functions.  They use polynomial identities, the binomial theorem, and Pascal’s Triangle to find roots of polynomials and roots of unity. Students compare and create different representations of functions while studying function composition, graphing functions, and finding inverse functions." Eureka Math/EngageNY (c) 2015 GreatMinds.org

title: Subtraction word problems within 10
description: Sal solves word problems by subtracting small numbers (numbers 10 or less).

title: Compare 2-digit numbers 2
description: Practice more challenging problems comparing numbers within 100.

title: Polymerase chain reaction (PCR)
description: A technique used to amplify, or make many copies of, a specific target region of DNA.

title: Word problems within 20
description: Learn how to solve addition and subtraction word problems. Numbers used are 20 or less.

title: Addition and subtraction word problems: superheroes

title: Global distribution of biodiversity
description: Explore how life is found almost everywhere on Earth, but is not distributed evenly. And learn why the clumped distributions of species are the result of a wide variety of both natural and human-driven factors. This content is provided by the California Academy of Sciences.

description: In this video, David explains two different strategies to deal with vertical springs and compares them with those used for horizontal springs.

That includes bacteria, worms and snakes, which might not be things you want covering the Earth's surface in a four-foot layer! Learn how populations grow and why real populations in nature always have limits on their growth.

description: Cambrian explosion and biodiversity in the Phanerozoic Eon

description: What population are you a part of? Humans, and other organisms, can be organized into populations - groups of organisms of the same species that are found in the same place. Learn about the tools ecologists use to study populations and predict how their numbers may change in the future.

title: Angular motion variables

description: Overview of competition, predation, herbivory, mutualism, commensalism, and parasitism.

description: Learn about expressions with rational exponents like x^(2/3), about radical expressions like √(2t^5), and about the relationship between these two forms of representation. Learn how to evaluate and simplify such expression.

description: Viruses of humans and other animals. The Baltimore classification. HIV life cycle.

description: Why do things move in circles? Seriously.  Why does *anything* ever move in a circle (straight lines seem much more natural)?  Is something moving in a circle at a constant speed accelerating?  If so, in what direction?  This tutorial will help you get your mind around this super-fun topic.

title: Addition word problem: starfish
description: Sal solves a word problem with the term "fewer".

title: Super hot tension
description: David shows how to solve a super hot tension problem where a can of peppers hangs from two diagonal strings.

title: Treating systems
description: When two or more objects must move with the same magnitude of acceleration (like masses on strings, or boxes pushed into each other), we can treat the entire system as a single object when finding the acceleration.

title: Gravitation (part 2)
description: A little bit more on gravity

title: Conservation of energy
description: Using the law of conservation of energy to see how potential energy is converted into kinetic energy

title: Evidence for evolution
description: Test your knowledge on the evidence for evolution!

title: Composing shapes
description: Practice making shapes from other shapes.

description: Introduction to Hooke's Law

description: Life and photosynthesis start to thrive in the Archean Eon

description: Thinking about evolutionary distance between species. Constructing phylogenetic trees (cladograms).

description: Learn what conservation of momentum means and how to use it.

description: Categorizing the different types of collisions can be useful. Here, you'll learn what it means for a collision to be elastic or inelastic and what that implies mathematically.

title: Functions
description:
Functions are mathematical entities that assign unique outputs to given inputs. Sounds simple? Think again!

In this topic you will evaluate, graph, analyze, and create various types of functions.

title: Scatterplots
description: Scatterplots show us relationships and patterns in data, and we use those patterns to make predictions.

title: Community ecology
description: Test your knowledge of community ecology!

title: Community structure & diversity
description: What makes ecological communities more or less stable to disturbances? What happens when an invasive species is introduced into a new environment? Learn how we can describe the structure of an ecological community and why a more diverse ecological community is usually more stable.

title: Normal force in an elevator
description: How the normal force changes when an elevator accelerates

title: Unbalanced forces and motion
description: Thinking about what is true about how unbalanced forces relate to motion and acceleration

description: Sal classifies shapes based on their number of sides, number of corners, and side-lengths.

title: Properties of shapes
description: Learn how different shapes have different numbers of corners, different side lengths, and so on. Use these properties to help you recognize shapes.

title: Telling time (unlabeled clock)
description: Sal tells time on unlabeled analog clocks.

description: How natural selection works at the level of genes, alleles, genotypes, & phenotypes.

description: Working through a calculation for K-Ar dating (good to have some prior experience with e and logarithms)

description: Learn about population growth rates and how they can be modeled by exponential and logistic equations.

title: Subtract 10s and 100s (no regrouping)

description: Sal shows some techniques for doing mental addition, such as making groups of 10 and 100.

description: Compare the lengths of 2 objects indirectly by using a third object.

title: Measuring lengths with different units
description: Use different units to measure the same object.

title: Making picture graphs and line plots
description: To create a line plot, ​first create a number line that includes all the values in the data set. Next, place an X (or dot) above each data value on the number line. If a value occurs more than once in a data set, place an Xs over that number for each time it occurs.

title: Natural selection and the owl butterfly
description: How the "Owl Butterfly" may have gotten the spot on its wings.

title: Work as the transfer of energy
description: David explains "work" as the way forces transfer energy to and from objects

title: Work/energy problem with friction
description: A conservation of energy problem where all of the energy is not conserved.

title: U.S. coins review
description: Review the value of U.S. coins, and try some practice problems.

title: Mechanical advantage
description: If you have ever used a tool of any kind (including the bones in your body), you have employed mechanical advantage.  Whether you used an incline plane to drag something off of a pick-up truck, or the back of a hammer to remove a nail, the world of mechanical advantage surrounds us.

title: Radiometric dating
description: Geologists and archaeologists will tell you how old things are or when they happened, but how do they know? This tutorial covers some of the primary techniques of "dating" (in the geological, not the romantic, sense!).

description: David explains what it means for a collision to be elastic or inelastic.

description: Introduction to moments

title: Data distributions
description: Data makes more sense when we graph it and summarize it with numbers.

title: Ecosystem services
description: Describing and quantifying the benefits that healthy ecosystems provide to humans. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Angular momentum
description: Introducing angular momentum conceptually starting from linear momentum. Also covers some real-life examples.

title: More on Normal force (shoe on floor)
description: David explains how to determine the normal force for a variety of scenarios (extra forces, diagonal forces, acceleration) involving a shoe on the floor.

title: Word problems within 100
description: Learn how to solve addition and subtraction word problems. Numbers used 100 or less.

title: Force of friction keeping the block stationary
description: Block of wood kept stationary by the force of friction (Correction made in next video)

title: What is friction?
description: Until now in physics, you've probably been ignoring friction to make things simpler. Now, it's time to include this very real force and see what happens.

title: Yo-yo in vertical circle example
description: In this video David explains how to find the tension in a string that is whirling a yo-yo in a vertical circle.

title: Length word problems
description: Learn how to solve length word problems.

title: Make bar graphs 1
description: Practice creating bar graphs (bar charts) from data sets.

title: Line plots review
description: Review the basics of lines plots and then practice creating and reading line plots.

title: Allele frequency & the gene pool
description: How to find allele frequency and how it's different from genotype frequency. What a gene pool is.

title: Equal parts of circles and rectangles
description: Practice telling if shapes are divided into 2 or 4 equal sections.

title: Biodiversity and natural selection
description: Patterns and processes of evolution. How evolution and natural selection are reflected in the similarities and differences of organisms. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Intro to ecology
description: Looking for an overview of core concepts in ecology? Just wondering what the heck ecology is? You're in the right place! Learn how organisms interact with each other and with their environment to make amazingly complex and beautiful networks.

title: Population size, density, & dispersal
description: What an ecological population is. How scientists define and measure population size, density, and distribution in space.

title: Relating angular and regular motion variables
description: In this video David shows how to relate the angular displacement to the arc length, angular velocity to the speed, and angular acceleration to the tangential acceleration.

title: Thomas Malthus and population growth
description: Thomas Malthus's views on population. Malthusian limits.

title: Strategies for adding 2-digit numbers
description: Sal goes through multiple strategies for adding 2-digit numbers.

title: Geometry transformations
description:
In this topic you will learn about the most useful math concept for creating video game graphics: geometric transformations, specifically translations, rotations, reflections, and dilations.

You will learn how to perform the transformations, and how to map one figure into another using these transformations.

title: Congruence
description: Learn what it means for two figures to be congruent, and how to determine whether two figures are congruent or not. Use this immensely important concept to prove various geometric theorems about triangles and parallelograms.

title: Constant angular momentum when no net torque
description: Just like how linear momentum is constant when there's no net force, angular momentum is constant where there's no net torque

title: Analytic geometry
description: In analytic geometry, also known as coordinate geometry, we think about geometric objects on the coordinate plane. For example, we can see that opposite sides of a parallelogram are parallel by by writing a linear equation for each side and seeing that the slopes are the same.

title: Angular momentum of an extended object
description: In this video David derives and shows how to use the formula for the angular momentum of an extended object.

title: Why biodiversity is distributed unevenly
description: Factors that influence the global distribution of biodiversity. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Ball hits rod angular momentum example
description: David explains how a mass can have angular momentum even if it is traveling along a straight line. Then David shows how to solve the conservation of angular momentum problem where a ball hits a rod which can rotate.

title: Threats to biodiversity
description: Examine the local and global threats to biodiversity that are caused by human activities. Many of the negative impacts start as regional, but easily add up to affect the entire planet. This content is provided by the California Academy of Sciences.

title: Ecological succession
description: Communities are dynamic and change over time, and we can observe this process with particular clarity after a disturbance or on new land. Learn about  primary and secondary succession, as well as pioneer species.

title: Human activities that threaten biodiversity
description: Human activities that cause a loss of biodiversity. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Ecological succession
description: Succession as progressive change in an ecological community. Primary vs. secondary succession. The idea of a climax community.

title: How does climate change affect biodiversity?
description: Effects of climate change on biodiversity. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Intro to ecosystems
description: What is an ecosystem? Well...it can be something as small as a tide pool,or as huge as the Amazon rainforest. But whatever size it may be, an ecosystem is made up of a community (populations of species interacting) plus their physical environment. Learn about different types of ecosystems and how energy flows through ecological communities.

title: Demystifying ocean acidification and biodiversity impacts
description: Why rising carbon dioxide levels in the atmosphere affect the acidity of the ocean, and what the consequences are for marine life. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: What is an ecosystem?
description: Learn what an ecosystem is, how energy and matter move through ecosystems, and what makes an ecosystem stable.

title: Absolute value & piecewise functions
description: Learn how to solve absolute value equations and how to graph absolute value functions.

title: Simple harmonic motion
description: Ever watch a slinky gyrate back and forth.  This is harmonic motion (a special class of oscillatory motion).  In this tutorial we'll see how we can model and deal with this type of phenomena.

title: Flow of energy and matter through ecosystems
description: Seeing how energy and matter flows and is recycled from primary producers (autotrophs) to primary, secondary and tertiary consumers.

title: Polynomials
description: Learn how to add, subtract, multiply, and divide polynomial expressions. For example, write (2x+3)(x-1) as 2x²+x-3.

title: Intuition about simple harmonic oscillators
description: David defines what it means for something to be a simple harmonic oscillator and gives some intuition about why oscillators do what they do as well as where the speed, acceleration, and force will be largest and smallest.

title: Protecting biodiversity
description: Research, education, individual action, and public policy all have important roles to play in protecting biodiversity. That means there's a lot you, personally, can do to preserve species and ecosystems - whoever you may be, and wherever you may live! This content is provided by the California Academy of Sciences.

title: Food chains & food webs
description: How food chains and food webs represent the flow of energy and matter. Trophic levels and efficiency of energy transfer.

title: Conservation and the race to save biodiversity
description: Different approaches to conservation and how they can protect species and habitats. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Irrational numbers
description: Learn about irrational numbers and how to identify them.

title: The water cycle
description: Learn how water moves through Earth's ecosystems.

title: Conic sections
description: Learn about two basic conic sections and their equations: Circle and Parabola.

title: Basic shapes
description: Learn the names of basic shapes, including circles, triangles, squares, and rectangles.

title: Subtraction within 100
description: Learn to subtract two-digit numbers like 47 and 39.

title: Adding 1s, 10s, and 100s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems by adding ones, tens, and hundreds.

title: Multiply by 8
description: Multiply 8 times a number less than or equal to 10.

title: Divide by 4
description: Divide by 4.  Quotients are less than or equal to 10.

title: Volume
description: Estimate the volume of items.  Solve word problems involving volume.

title: Creating bar graphs
description: Practice creating bar graphs to represent data.

title: Reading bar graphs: Harry Potter
description: Sal interprets a bar graph.

title: Definition of amplitude and period
description: David defines the terms amplitude and period for simple harmonic motion and shows how to find them on a graph.

title: Factorization
description: Learn how to write polynomial expressions as the product of linear factors. For example, write x^2+3x+2 as (x+1)(x+2).

title: Equation for simple harmonic oscillators
description: David explains the equation that represents the motion of a simple harmonic oscillator and solves an example problem.

title: Energy flow & primary productivity
description: Learn about primary productivity, the (in)efficiency of energy transfer between trophic levels, and how to read ecological pyramids.

title: Period dependence for mass on spring
description: David explains what affects the period of a mass on a spring (i.e. mass and spring constant). He also explains what does not affect the period of a mass on a spring (i.e. amplitude and gravitational acceleration).

title: Phase constant
description: In this video David explains how a phase constant can be used in order to shift the graph of an oscillator left or right.

title: Levels of biodiversity
description: Learn how to recognize the genetic, ecosystem, and evolutionary levels of biodiversity. Along with species richness, these levels play crucial roles in conservation. Content provided by the California Academy of Sciences.

title: Biogeochemical cycles
description: "Atoms get recycled." That may not sound too exciting. But think of it this way: some of the atoms in your body right now were once almost certainly part of trees, rocks, various animals, other human beings, and even dinosaurs! Learn more about how matter is recycled in Earth's ecosystems and why the water, carbon, nitrogen, and phosphorous cycles are so important to living things.

title: Pendulums
description: David explains how a pendulum can be treated as a simple harmonic oscillator, and then explains what affects, as well as what does not affect, the period of a pendulum.

title: Genes and biodiversity
description: How does the gene pool contribute to biodiversity? Learn how genetic diversity within populations contributes to species survival. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Intro to biogeochemical cycles
description: Get an overview of how atoms are recycled through Earth's ecosystems via biogeochemical cycles.

title: Exponential growth & decay
description: Learn how to analyze and manipulate exponential functions and expressions in order to study their rate of change.

title: Ecosystem biodiversity
description: Are all coral reefs the same?  Each regional ecosystem has its own assemblage of species and each contributes uniquely to global biodiversity. Explore why ecosystem diversity is important for conservation decisions. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Biogeochemical cycles overview
description: Introduction to how water, carbon, nitrogen, and phosphorus are cycled through ecosystems.

title: Introduction to harmonic motion
description: Harmonic motion refers to the motion an oscillating mass experiences when the restoring force is proportional to the ​displacement, but in opposite directions. Harmonic motion is periodic and can be represented by a sine wave with constant frequency and amplitude. An example of this is a weight bouncing on a spring.

title: Similarity
description: Learn what it means for two figures to be similar, and how to determine whether two figures are similar or not. Use this concept to prove geometric theorems and solve some problems with polygons.

title: Levels of biodiversity
description: Test your knowledge on the levels of biodiversity!

title: Harmonic motion part 2 (calculus)
description: We test whether Acos(wt) can describe the motion of the mass on a spring by substituting into the differential equation F=-kx

title: The water cycle
description: How the sun's energy drives the water cycle on Earth.

title: Right triangles & trigonometry
description: Triangles are not always right (although they are never wrong), but when they are it opens up an exciting world of possibilities.  Not only are right triangles cool in their own right (pun intended), they are the basis of very important ideas in analytic geometry (the distance between two points in space) and trigonometry.

title: Harmonic motion part 3 (no calculus)
description: Figuring out the period, frequency, and amplitude of the harmonic motion of a mass attached to a spring.

title: The carbon cycle
description: Learn how carbon moves through Earth's ecosystems and how human activities are altering the carbon cycle.

title: Solid geometry
description: Extend your knowledge about two-dimensional shapes to three dimensions!

title: Introduction to mechanical waves
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn the definition of a wave and the difference between transverse and longitudinal waves. You'll also learn the definition of the basic terms used to characterize waves; amplitude, period, frequency, and wavelength.

title: The carbon cycle
description: Overview of how carbon is recycled through our biosphere in the carbon cycle.

title: Circles
description: Explore, prove, and apply important properties of circles that have to do with things like arc length, radians, inscribed angles, and tangents.

title: Introduction to waves
description: Introduction to transverse and longitudinal waves

title: The nitrogen cycle
description: The key role of microbes in nitrogen fixation. How overuse of nitrogen-containing fertilizers can cause algal blooms.

title: Properties of periodic waves
description: Amplitude, period, frequency and wavelength of periodic waves. How to calculate wave velocity.

title: Multiplication intro
description: Welcome to the concept of multiplication.

title: Time
description: Learn how to tell time on analog clocks.

Animal behavior
description: How do songbirds learn to sing? Why do ants follow invisible lines to sources of food? What are dogs trying to accomplish when they mark their territory? Learn about these and many other fascinating, diverse, and sometimes bizarre examples of animal behavior.

title: The nitrogen cycle
description: How nitrogen is recycled in our biosphere in the nitrogen cycle, including nitrogen fixation.

title: Intro to animal behavior
description: What exactly counts as behavior? What triggers behaviors? Are they hard-wired in animals' genes, or learned based on experience?

title: Probability
description: Few things are certain in life. Probability gives us an idea of the likelihood or unlikelihood of different outcomes.

title: The equation of a wave
description: In this video David shows how to determine the equation of a wave, how that equation works, and what the equation represents.

title: The phosphorous cycle
description: The slow cycling of phosphorous through the biosphere. How phosphorous-containing fertilizers can cause aquatic dead zones.

title: Innate behaviors
description: Learn about behaviors that are pre-programmed into an animal's genes, including reflexes and fixed action patterns.

title: Sound
description: In these videos and articles you'll see visualizations of the propagation of sound waves, along with a visual definition of a sound wave's amplitude, period, frequency, and wavelength. You'll also learn how the speed of sound depends on the different characteristics of the medium. It will be shown how Mach numbers characterize faster than sound travel and their relationship to sonic booms. Also, you'll learn about the decibel scale, why sounds get softer, and how ultrasound medical imaging works.

title: Phosphorous cycle
description: Introduction to the phosphorous cycle. How phosphorus is recycled from phosphate to ATP and DNA.

title: Production of sound
description: Sound is vibrating air. But how does the air start vibrating?

title: Learned behaviors
description: Habituation, imprinting, classical conditioning, operant conditioning, and cognitive learning.

title: Eutrophication and dead zones
description: How eutrophication, caused by extra nutrients in runoff, can lead to dead zones.

title: Animal communication

These videos do not provide medical advice and are for informational purposes only. The videos are not intended to be a substitute for professional medical advice, diagnosis or treatment. Always seek the advice of a qualified health provider with any questions you may have regarding a medical condition. Never disregard professional medical advice or delay in seeking it because of something you have read or seen in any Khan Academy video.

title: Sound Properties: Amplitude, period, frequency, wavelength
description: How to find the amplitude, period, frequency, and wavelength for a sound wave

title: Animal communication
description: Learn how animals communicate with visual, sound, touch, and chemical signals.

title: Functions
description: A great cook knows how to take basic ingredients and prepare a delicious meal. In this topic, you will become function-chefs! You will learn how to combine functions with arithmetic operations and how to compose functions. You will also learn how to transform functions in ways that shift, reflect, or stretch their graphs. Finally, you will learn about inverse functions and how to find them!

title: Biogeochemical cycles
description: Test your knowledge of biogeochemical cycles!

title: Relative speed of sound in solids, liquids, and gases
description: Sounds travels at different speeds in different media

title: Polynomials
description: Learn how to manipulate polynomials in order to prove identities and find the zeros of those polynomials. Use this knowledge to solve polynomial equations and graph polynomial functions. Learn about symmetry of functions.

title: Biogeography
description: Have you ever noticed that different types of animals and plants are found in different places? Learn about some of the factors behind patterns of species distribution and abundance.

title: Radical relationships
description: In this topic you will learn how to solve radical equations (which are equations with radical expressions in them) while avoiding extraneous solutions. You will also learn how to graph radical functions.

title: Decibel Scale
description: We often use this logarithmic scale to describe the intensity of sound

title: Rational relationships
description: Rational expressions are like fractions, but instead of integers in the numerator and the denominator, you have variable expressions! Learn how to work with such expressions. Namely, simplify, add, subtract, multiply, and divide them (much like fractions!). Then, solve some equations with rational expressions in them, and analyze the behavior of rational functions.

title: Why do sounds get softer?
description: Let's think about why sounds would have to get softer as you get further from the source

title: Exponentials & logarithms
description: Learn about logarithms, which are the inverses of exponents. Use logarithms to solve various equations. Then analyze both logarithmic and exponential functions and their graphs.

title: Doppler effect formula when source is moving away
description: Let's look at the case where the source is moving away from the listener

title: Pressure at a depth in a fluid
description: Sal derives the formula to determine the pressure at a specific depth in a fluid.

title: Density and Pressure
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn the definitions of density and specific gravity. You'll also learn the definition of pressure, how it relates to force and area, and how to determine the pressure within a fluid. The difference between absolute and gauge pressure will also be discussed.

title: Tolerance ranges of species
description: Abiotic (non-living) factors that influence where a species can live.

title: Ultrasound medical imaging
description: Ultrasound medical imaging (also known as sonography) is a diagnostic imaging tool that uses high-frequency sound waves to create images of structures in the body. Ultrasound images are captured in ​real time​ using an external probe and ultrasound gel placed directly on the skin. They can show things that a still image like an X-ray cannot, such as blood flow or organ movement. Ultrasound images are highly useful in the diagnosis and treatment of many diseases.

title: Specific gravity
description: In this video David explains what specific gravity means. He also shows how to calculate the value for specific gravity and use it to determine the percent of an object that will be submerged while floating.

title: Trigonometry
description: Learn about the definition of the basic trigonometric functions (sin(x), cos(x), and tan(x)), and use advanced trigonometric functions for various purposes.

title: The Doppler effect
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how the Doppler effect causes a change in the measured frequency of a moving source of sound or moving sound detector. You'll also learn how to calculate the observed frequency using the formula for the Doppler effect when dealing with either a moving source of sound or a moving sound detector.

title: Climate
description: Global, regional, and local factors that influence climate. How climate affects where species are found.

title: Pressure and Pascal's principle (part 1)
description: Sal explains the difference between liquids and gasses (both fluids). He then starts a calculation of the work done on a liquid in a U-shaped container.

title: Advanced equations & functions
description: Solve advanced equations by graphing. Interpret advanced features of functions (like symmetry, end behavior, and periodicity) in terms of their context, and compare features of various types of functions.

title: Doppler effect introduction
description: Learn about the Doppler effect and how it explains the change in frequency of a wave when its source and an observer are moving.

title: Pressure and Pascal's principle (part 2)
description: Sal finishes the calculation of work to determine the mechanical advantage in a U-shaped tube. He also explains pressure and Pascal's Principle.

title: Doppler effect formula for observed frequency
description: Let's derive the formula for how the perceived frequency of a sound changes when its source is moving toward you

title: Study Design
description: Getting reliable data is vital if we want to make correct conclusions.The process of collecting data through studies involves sampling, observations, surveys, and experiments.

title: Binomial probability
description: If you roll five dice, what’s the probability that three of them show a 6? In a group of 20 strangers, what’s the probability that more than half of them were born in the summer? Learn about binomial probability to answer these types of problems.

title: When the source and the wave move at the same velocity
description: What happens when both the listener and the source are moving together?

title: Finding height of fluid in a barometer
description: Using our understanding of fluid pressure to figure out the height of a column of mercury.

title: Normal distributions
description: A Normal distribution is a very special and common distribution that is fundamental to learning about statistics. Normal distributions describe many real world phenomena from scores on exams to lengths of wings on bugs.

title: Doppler effect for a moving observer
description: What happens when just the observer is moving?

title: Body structure & homeostasis
description: What makes a tissue different from an organ? How does your stomach collaborate with your small intestine to make sure you get nutrients? And most important, how do the systems of your body keep things like your temperature and blood pH from getting too high or too low? Keep reading and watching to find answers to all of these questions!

title: Buoyant Force and Archimedes' Principle
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how pressure variations cause a buoyant force on a submerged object and how to calculate the value of the buoyant force. You'll also learn the meaning of Archimedes' principle.

title: Doppler effect: reflection off a moving object
description: Does the doppler effect still apply when sound is being reflected off a moving object?

title: Tissues, organs, & organ systems
description: Learn about the main tissue types and organ systems of the body and how they work together.

title: Archimedes principle and buoyant force
description: Introduction to Archimedes' principle and buoyant force.

title: Wave interference
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how standing waves are produced and how to determine the wavelength and frequency of the different harmonics of standing waves produced in an open open tube or an open closed tube.

title: Adding 1s and 10s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems like 23+4 and 23+40.

title: Measuring length
description: Learn how to measure length using unit squares and rulers.

title: Skip-counting
description: Learn to count by fives, tens, and hundreds.

title: Comparing and estimating length
description: Learn how to compare and estimate length.

title: What is buoyant force?
description: Why the heck do things float?

title: Homeostasis
description: Learn how organisms maintain homeostasis, or a stable internal environment.

title: Wave interference
description: David explains wave interference and solves a few examples to find the value of the total wave when two wave pulses overlap.

title: Body structure and homeostasis
description: Test your knowledge of body structure and homeostasis!

title: Buoyant force example problems
description: A couple of problems involving Archimedes' principle and buoyant forces.

title: Constructive and Destructive interference
description: In this video David explains what constructive and destructive interference means as well as how path length differences and pi shifts affect the interference.

title: Metabolism & thermoregulation
description: You may think of metabolism as something that humans have (such as a fast or a slow metabolism). But metabolism is just the sum total of chemical reactions that occur in an organism's body, and all organisms must metabolize to keep their bodies running. Learn more about metabolism and how it's connected to thermoregulation (temperature regulation) in different species of animals.

title: Fluid Dynamics
description: Flowing fluids behave different from static fluids. In these videos and articles you'll learn about volume flow rate and the equation of continuity. You'll also learn how Bernoulli's principle and Bernoulli's equation relate the pressure and speed of a flowing fluid. The effects of turbulence and viscosity will also be discussed.

title: Metabolic rate
description: Metabolism of endotherms and ectotherms. Basal metabolic rate and standard metabolic rate. How metabolic rate varies with body size and activity level.

title: Standing waves on strings
description: David explains how and why standing waves occur, and well as how to determine the wavelengths for a standing wave on a string.

title: Volume flow rate and equation of continuity
description: Sal introduces the notion of moving fluids and laminar flow. Then he uses the incompressibility of a liquid to show that the volume flow rate (flux) must remain constant. Sal then derives the equation of continuity in terms of the area and speed.

title: Endotherms & ectotherms
description: The difference between endotherms and ectotherms. How to read graphs related to endotherms and ectotherms.

title: Standing waves in open tubes
description: Find out why a flute makes such specific notes

title: What is volume flow rate?
description: You know all about the motion of individual objects. Now, let's talk about how to analyze the motion of a fluid.

title: What is the first law of thermodynamics?
description: Learn what the first law of thermodynamics is and how to use it.

title: Proof: S (or entropy) is a valid state variable
description: Proof that S (or entropy) is a valid state variable.

title: 2015 AP Biology free response, 1d-e
description: Light-dark activity cycle of mutant mice and evolutionary implications.

title: Pith ball electroscope
description: Primitive device for measuring electrostatic force

title: Temperature regulation strategies
description: How behavior, anatomy, and physiology help animals regulate body temperature.

title: Thermoregulation

title: Derivation of beat frequency formula
description: In this video David derives the formula for beat frequency.

description: Clarification of, and more thoughts on, the Bernoulli's equation example problem where liquid exits a hole in a container.

title: Bernoulli's example problem
description: Sal solves a Bernoulli's equation example problem where fluid is moving through a pipe of varying diameter.

title: What is Bernoulli's equation?
description: This equation will give you the powers to analyze a fluid flowing up and down through all kinds of different tubes.

title: Viscosity and Poiseuille flow
description: David explains the concept of viscosity, viscous force, and Poiseuille's law.

title: Temperature, kinetic theory, and the ideal gas law
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn about the Celsius and Kelvin temperature scales. The definition of a mole of a substance will be given. You'll also learn how the ideal gas law relates the pressure, volume, and temperature of a gas. Lastly, you'll learn how the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution gives the probability of finding a gas molecule moving at a specific speed.

title: Work from expansion
description: How a system can do work by expanding

title: Inflammatory response
description: Overview of the inflammatory response.

description: In this topic, we will add and subtract whole numbers. The topic starts with 1+1=2 and goes through adding and subtracting within 1000.  We will cover regrouping, borrowing, and word problems.

title: Turbulence at high velocities and Reynold's number
description: In this video David explains how the Reynold's number allows you to determine the speed at which fluid flow becomes turbulent.

title: Thermodynamics part 1: Molecular theory of gases
description: Intuition of how gases generate pressure in a container and why pressure x volume is proportional to the combined kinetic energy of the molecules in the volume.

title: Multiplication and division
description: In this topic, we will multiply and divide whole numbers. The topic starts with 1-digit multiplication and division and goes through multi-digit problems.  We will cover regrouping, remainders, and word problems.

title: Venturi effect and Pitot tubes
description: David explains the Venturi effect and the role and function of Pitot tubes.

title: Thermodynamics part 2: Ideal gas law
description: To begin, Sal solves a constant temperature problem using PV=PV. Then he relates temperature to kinetic energy of a gas. In the second half of the video, he derives the ideal gas law.

title: Negative numbers
description: Learn about numbers below 0 and how they relate to positive numbers.  Add, subtract, multiply and divide negative numbers.

title: Surface Tension and Adhesion
description: David explains the concepts of surface tension, cohesion, and adhesion.

title: Phototropism
description: Phototropism and the role that auxin plays.

title: Capacitance
description: Introduction to the capacitance of a two-plate capacitor.

title: The dot product
description: Introduction to the vector dot product.

title: Composing shapes
description: Practice making shapes from other shapes.

title: Kirchhoff's loop rule
description: Learn how to analyze the voltage in a DC circuit using Kirchhoff loop rule (or voltage law).

description: Sal makes the case for the Kelvin scale of temperature and absolute zero by showing that temperature is proportional to kinetic energy. Then he explains that you need to use the Kelvin scale in the ideal gas law. To finish he does a sample ideal gas law problem.

title: Fractions
description: In this topic, we will explore fractions conceptually and add, subtract, multiply, and divide fractions.

title: Thermodynamics part 4: Moles and the ideal gas law
description: Sal explains the concept of a mole. Then he derives the molar version of the ideal gas law PV=nRT, where the gas constant R=831 J/molK.

title: Decimals
description: In this topic, we will learn what a decimal is and how to show it visually and on a number line.  We will also add, subtract, multiply, and divide with decimals.

title: Thermodynamics part 5: Molar ideal gas law problem
description: Sal uses the molar version of the ideal gas law to solve for the number of moles in a gas. He also shows how to convert this answer into number of molecules using Avogadro's number.

title: What is the ideal gas law?
description: Learn how pressure, volume, temperature, and the amount of a gas are related to each other.

title: Circulatory and pulmonary systems
description: As humans, we really like breathing oxygen.  That's because the cells in our body will die if they don't get the oxygen they need to function.  This tutorial describes how gases are exchanged between blood and the atmosphere in our lungs, and how oxygen is then pumped through the body by way of blood and the circulatory system.

title: Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution
description: Using the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution to visualize the distribution of speeds of particles at different temperatures.

title: Specific heat and heat transfer
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn the definition of specific heat and latent heat and how to use them in problem solving. You'll also learn the 3 modes of heat transfer; conduction, convection, and radiation. Lastly, we will look in more depth at how the rate of thermal conduction through a material depends on the material's thickness, conductivity constant, area, and difference in temperature.

description: Neurons are specialized cells that allow our bodies to transmit signals from one part to another quickly.  In this tutorial, we'll explore the anatomy of a neuron and the mechanism by which neurons transmit signals.

title: Anatomy of a neuron
description: Neurons (or nerve cells) are specialized cells that transmit and receive electrical signals in the body. Neurons are composed of three main parts: dendrites, a cell body, and an axon. Signals are received through the dendrites, travel to the cell body, and continue down the axon until they reach the synapse (the communication point between two neurons).

Length word problems

description: Learn how to count U.S. coins and dollars.

title: What is thermal conductivity?
description: Read this article to learn how to determine the rate at which heat conducts through a material.

title: Sodium-potassium pump
description: How a sodium potassium pump can maintain a voltage gradient across a cell or neuron's membrane.

title: Laws of thermodynamics
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how the first law of thermodynamics relates the change in internal energy of a gas, heat that enters the gas, and work done on the gas. PV diagrams will be discussed, as well as the four common thermal processes: isobaric, isochoric/isovolumetric, isothermal, and adiabatic. You'll also learn about how the second law of thermodynamics relates the entropy change to the multiplicity of microstates and the heat that enters a macroscopic system. The efficiency of a heat engine will also be explained.

title: Correction to sodium-potassium pump video
description: Correction to "Sodium-potassium pump" video.

title: Macrostates and microstates
description: In physics, a microstate is defined as the arrangement of each molecule in the system at a single instant. A macrostate is defined by the macroscopic properties of the system, such as temperature, pressure, volume, etc. For each macrostate, there are many microstates which result in the same macrostate.
